<h1 id="linux-permissions">Linux Permissions</h1>
<h3 id="user-account-management">User Account Management</h3>
<h4 id="creating-a-user-account-—-useradd">1.Creating a User Account — <code>useradd</code></h4>
<p><strong>What it does:</strong> Creates a new user account on the system.</p>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">useradd</span> username
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Common flags:</strong></p>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">useradd</span> -m username        <span class="token comment"># Create home directory</span>
<span class="token function">useradd</span> -m -s /bin/bash username   <span class="token comment"># Set default shell</span>
<span class="token function">useradd</span> -m -G <span class="token function">sudo</span> username        <span class="token comment"># Add to sudo group on creation</span>
<span class="token function">useradd</span> -m -c <span class="token string">"Full Name"</span> username <span class="token comment"># Add comment/full name</span>
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Real behaviour:</strong> Without <code>-m</code>, no home directory is created — the user exists but can’t log in properly.</p>
<hr>
<h4 id="setting-a-password-—-passwd">2.Setting a Password — <code>passwd</code></h4>
<p><strong>What it does:</strong> Sets or changes a user’s password.</p>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">passwd</span> username         <span class="token comment"># Set password for a user (as root)</span>
<span class="token function">passwd</span>                  <span class="token comment"># Change your own password</span>
<span class="token function">passwd</span> -l username      <span class="token comment"># Lock a user account</span>
<span class="token function">passwd</span> -u username      <span class="token comment"># Unlock a user account</span>
<span class="token function">passwd</span> -e username      <span class="token comment"># Force password change on next login</span>
</code></pre>
<hr>
<h4 id="modifying-a-user-—-usermod">3.Modifying a User — <code>usermod</code></h4>
<p><strong>What it does:</strong> Modifies an existing user account.</p>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">usermod</span> -aG <span class="token function">sudo</span> username        <span class="token comment"># Add user to sudo group</span>
<span class="token function">usermod</span> -aG docker,nginx username <span class="token comment"># Add to multiple groups</span>
<span class="token function">usermod</span> -s /bin/zsh username     <span class="token comment"># Change shell</span>
<span class="token function">usermod</span> -l newname oldname       <span class="token comment"># Rename user</span>
<span class="token function">usermod</span> -L username              <span class="token comment"># Lock account</span>
<span class="token function">usermod</span> -U username              <span class="token comment"># Unlock account</span>
</code></pre>
<p>⚠️ Always use <code>-aG</code> (append + group), never just <code>-G</code> — without <code>-a</code> it <strong>replaces</strong> all existing groups.</p>
<hr>
<h4 id="deleting-a-user-—-userdel">4.Deleting a User — <code>userdel</code></h4>
<p><strong>What it does:</strong> Removes a user account from the system.</p>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">userdel</span> username          <span class="token comment"># Delete user only</span>
<span class="token function">userdel</span> -r username       <span class="token comment"># Delete user + home directory + mail spool</span>
</code></pre>
<hr>
<h4 id="viewing-users--groups">5.Viewing Users &amp; Groups</h4>
<p>bash</p>
<pre class=" language-bash"><code class="prism  language-bash"><span class="token function">cat</span> /etc/passwd           <span class="token comment"># All users on the system</span>
<span class="token function">cat</span> /etc/group            <span class="token comment"># All groups</span>
<span class="token function">id</span> username               <span class="token comment"># User's UID, GID, and groups</span>
<span class="token function">groups</span> username           <span class="token comment"># Groups a user belongs to</span>
<span class="token function">who</span>                       <span class="token comment"># Currently logged-in users</span>
last                      <span class="token comment"># Login history</span>
</code></pre>
